Preprocessing¶

Clean the Data¶

The first thing I did here was to clean the data. While randomly going through the dataset, I noticed some issues with the data:

  1. The data contains web links but the url's are seperated by spaces e.g "http : / google . co"

  2. The data contains lots of characters and numbers.

  3. The data contains many whitespaces.

  4. The data contains some single characters.
    5. </ol> To deal with the issues above, I used regular expressions to fix them as they constitute noise and would affect the performance of the model. I also noticed that the word "Subject" appears both in Spam and Ham messages, as this cannot be used to distinguish between Spam and Ham, I removed the word. The code below shows the codes that were used.

In [191]:
#Remove non alphabets(Numbers and punctuation marks)
import re
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('[^a-zA-Z]',' ',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
In [192]:
# Substituting multiple spaces with a single space
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('\s+',' ',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
In [193]:
# remove all single characters
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('\s+[a-zA-Z]\s+',' ',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
In [194]:
# remove parts of web url and also the word "Subject"
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('http','',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('www','',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('nbsp','',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('subject','',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]
hamSpamData["Emails"] = [re.sub('com','',doc) for doc in hamSpamData["Emails"] ]

Feature Extraction¶

Stemming¶

Stemming which is the process of reducing words to their root form was used in order to have better sets of features and not having same variant of a word as features. The NLTK library was used for this as I used the porterStemmer function to achieve this. This was done on both the train and test set.

In [200]:
#Stemming- For finding the root words and using it to avoid having smae words with different forms as a feature
from nltk.stem.porter import PorterStemmer
stemmer = PorterStemmer()

def stemWords(words) :
    stemmedWords = list()
    for word in words :
        newWord = stemmer.stem(word)
        stemmedWords.append(newWord)
    return stemmedWords

X_train=pd.Series([" ".join(stemWords(doc.split())) for doc in X_train])
X_test=pd.Series([" ".join(stemWords(doc.split())) for doc in X_test])

Pipeline for Feature Extraction and Modelling¶

A pipeline was used for both feature extraction and modelling as can be seen below. A varieties of models were used which includes:

  1. Bernoulli Naive Bayes
  2. Multinomial Naive Bayes
  3. Gaussian Naive Bayes
  4. Support Vector Machines

The process for all the model pipelines follows this process:

  1. Extract features from the document:
    2. As machine learning models cant take in text data, the first thing I did was to transform each word into a numerical feature using the bag of words model. I used count vectorizer from the SKLearn library for this as it generates all unique words from the document(emails) and then creates a matrix of the document(emails)(row) by the words(columns) which are the features, then the values are the number of occurence of the words in each of those documents. It also creates a dictionary of all the vocabularies from the documents(emails).
  2. TF-IDF Encoding:
    3. Since the emails are are of different lengths, this means that more weights would be given to longer documents as they would contain more words. In order to normalize this, I used the TfidfTransformer from SKLearn. What it does is to divide the count of each word in a document(email) by the total words in that document(email). Also, this also reduces the weigths of words that occurs in all of the document(emails) as they do not tell us much about the outcome class.
  3. Fit the data to the model:
    4. The last thing is to fit the model with this transformed data.

After creating the pipeline, using the cross_val_score function, I divided my training data into 10 folds using cv=10 and then performed a cross validation using the training data 10 times and then got an average of the model's accuracy. This was done to have a better accuracy of the model and not get an accuracy that was due to chance or due to the data split that was used.

The accuracy for the 4 models were then compared using a bar plot which can be seen below. The plot shows that Support Vector Machines has an higher accuracy when compared to the Naive Bayes variants.

Parameter Tuning using Grid Search¶

In order to get better results, I decided to tune the various models across various parameters using a grid search. The GridSearchCV was used for this from the SKLearn library also.

The parameters I tuned across all the pipelines are:

  1. Ngram Range:
    2. I gave as parameters "unigram" and "bigram" to the count vectorizer in order to determine which was better.
  2. Maximum Features:
    3. Maximum features to use for the count vectorizer was also given as parameters with the following sets of values:
    • 1,000
    • 5,000
    • 10,000
    • None
  3. Stop Words:
    4. Stop words are words which do not add much information to sentences hence, they are most times not useful in text classification problems. What I did was to remove "english" stopwords and also not to remove stopwords in order to determine which would give better results.
  4. TFID Encoding:
    5. Finally, I passed both "True" and "False" in order to determine which gave better accuracy. Whether it was when tfid transformer was used or not.

Instances of the grid search was created for each of the models and using 5 fold cross validation, I computed the best score and also got the best parameters for each of the models.

The code is shown below.

plt.title("Model Accuracy")
plt.xlabel('Model Type')

Selecting Best Model¶

Based on the accuracy from the tuned models, I settled with the SVM model as it has a better accuracy. The next step was to create a new pipeline using the best parameters gotten from the grid search. The model's accuracy was then evaluated using 10 cross validation validation on the train data. A mean accuracy of 98.45% was gotten which is slightly more than the 98.26% gotten before the tuning. Also, the accuracy score for the 10 times it was evaluated is plotted below.

Conclusion¶

Even with an accuracy of 98.90%, from the confusion matrix, it shows that 14 mails were wrongly classified as Spam when they were not and they end up in the Spam folder. This cost is higher as it means important and legitimate emails can end up in the Spam folder. However, having a f1-score of 0.99 for Ham class and 0.98 for Spam class is very good.
